	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'd do with smaller sprites. Why do we need so big sprites ? The inconvegnient of fighting game is that everything is about character graphics, but doing the characters the size they are in Double Dragon (I think it is 5x2 tiles) is okay. If you would kick or something it will never overpass 4 tiles wide per character. Maybe if they are lying on the ground it would be 5 tiles large, but it is rare that both characters are lying on the ground at the same time.</div>
<br />That's the approach used in the Datach games. The players are very small, much smaller than any other fighting games. It kinda looks nice, but I'd like to see a good fighting game with large, detailed characters for once. A mapper with CHR switching would be needed though, as it would be impossible to keep all the graphics of big characters loaded at once or to use CHR-RAM and draw such large ammounts of tiles on the fly.
<br />
<br />EDIT: I've been playing with sprite sizes a bit, and came to the conclusion that the smalest size a fighting game character can be is 24x48 pixels. and even then the guy is a bit squashed within those dimensions (this is scaled by 2):
<br />
<br /><img src="http://www.nesstuff.kit.net/fighter01.gif" alt="Image" />
<br />I believe that anything less than that won't feel like a fighting game. The extra column to the right should be used when kicking and punching, but that may not be enough for certain moves. With this size, there would be no flickering for most of the time, but when both characters are attacking and some effects are showing, it will flicker a bit. Of course, this is with both characters as sprites, and a regular background behind them.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
